author: MilanGajic

title: CTC Heated Build Platform Thermistor Fix

description.text:
Many, many owners find that the Heated Build Platform on their CTC Dual Printer (which is a clone of the Flashforge Creator, which is in itself a clone of the Makerbot Replicator Dual), is woefully badly calibrated.

The HBP is based on the original Replicator HBP ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16061 ), but the PCB layout is tweaked to make space for a largish (~7mm) thermistor, or a 1206 SMD part (only 1 should be fitted though).

In many ways, it doesn't really matter if the displayed (set) temperature doesn't match the real HBP temperature, so long as it's consistent. However, on my CTC, it was out such that a set temperature of 90C resulted in a platform temperature of about 60 degrees, and the maximum allowed set temperature of 130 degrees resulted in an actual platform temperature of 90 C. That's not good enough - the inaccuracy means the HBP isn't really hot enough for reliable ABS prints.

The reason for the discrepancy is that CTC chose the wrong part for the thermistor. I'm not sure what the part is they used, but it's beta is way out of the required beta.

I'm running Sailfish 7.7, and according to the source code, the firmware is designed to work with a 100k thermistor with beta 4066K with R2 at 4.7K.

So, replacing the thermistor with a better part will fix the problem.

I chose to use an EPCOS B57540G0104J thermistor. Which is absolutely tiny, but works very well. You should be able to find one on RS, Digikey, Farnell, the usual suspects.

Step 1

Remove the HBP by fully removing the 4 bed levelling wing nuts, and disconnecting the power connector

Step 2

See the original thermistor in the centre of the board. Use your soldering iron and a solder sucker and/or solder wick to remove it. Worth keeping as a spare.

Step 3

The two unused pads next to the thermistor are where we'll solder the new one.

The new thermistor is tiny. Make sure the legs are not twisted and shorting out before you install it. Step 4

Solder the new thermistor about an inch away, onto the SMD pads. Apply a small piece of kapton tape to keep the bead of the thermistor in contact with the board.

Finished, with a piece of kapton tape to hold the thermister against the board Step 5

Reassemble the printer. Make sure to tighten the levelling nuts a lot so the platform is definitely low enough to start your bed levelling procedure. You don't want to ram your extruder into the side of it.

Finished!

Use the monitor tool in ReplicatorG to set a test temperature for the HBP

Now the temperatures measured on the underside of the HBP are within about 2% of the set temp, and the surface temperature is a little lower than that.

When I set 130 degrees, the underside of mine is at 127 and the top surface gets to 118.

Perfect!

Happy Printing.

description.text:
Rear axle for the printed truck V1!

This is the axle housing plus the differential gears, it will behave like a locked differential with this setup.
I might make an open differential sometime but not in the near future as I only care about maximum traction with this.

It needs:
4mm axle, length depends on wheels
4mm bearings, I used 624zz bearings.
M3 grubscrews for locking the gears(M3x4 should work)

You will also need rodends and suitable rods for connecting the axle to the frame.

Seems to run fine without oil/grease but adding some thick grease probably wouldn't hurt.

You can see a demo of the complete truck here:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rr9fuMH2_O4

Basically documenting what I did --. This is my first redesign/remix of anything.

Quick summary is - Tinkercard - Right Side Menu, shape-makers community for curved, shape-makers-tinkercad for the numbers.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2

Scenario

A patron came to the maker space, wanting to make a 3d-printed cake for a friend's birthday.

We wanted the lowest learning curve, thinking Tinkercard, except Victoria thought all letters there were only drag-n-drop.

Fortunately, I spent some time a few weeks ago poking around TinkerCad (and I haven't had a chance to look at Autodesk123 or anything else), so I knew there were easier text options within it, including a curve.

Process

found the Birthday Cake by gmillener, and with Victoria's help, we customized it for a client at UMD to take to a birthday party

I uploaded the STL to TinkerCad.

Under the right-side menu, chose "shape-makers, community" and found "custom font text" which appeared curved, by Glen Reimche.

Victoria has amazing skills of positioning and proportion, and adjusted the dimensions (degree of curve, diameter) and locations.

Then in the same right-side menu, under "shape-makers - Tinkercad" chose "Text" by Tinkercad. All the other fonts looked odd for the number, so we went back to the default.

Again, Victoria positioned it to embed into the cake.

(We tried lower case text, but to make it connect to the birthday cake part, we then lost back part of "happy". We also removed the comma for the same reason.)

Not sure what size they chose to print it out. The patron chose the goldenish color, as it seems like cake.

description.text:
Problem: I teach classes where we build amsat antennas and try to listen to satellites and the International Space Station. It is really hard to point to nothing at all, so I thought this would help (at least, during the night). It also has the handy dandy feature that it can be used to point out astronomical items if you modify the pyephem script barely (I'll include another program to run for this I think).

This thing points things out to you using a laser pointer in the night. It should probably never be used unattended unless you want the police to come by because you shone a light right into an airplane on approach.

It was designed to run on a pi but can also run on a laptop etc. It runs a python script which loads a TLE located in TLE.txt in the same and sends alt+az commands through the serial port to the arduino. The arduino decodes the alt+az and commands the servo and stepper accordingly. I implemented a horrible motion algorithm for the servo because it was really shaking my laser all over, but the stepper is just linear motion so there is room for improvement.

Enjoy!

Video here: https://youtu.be/uu8M_wjfsk4

This catapult is made with the 2016 FIRST Robotics medieval theme in mind to be a handout to other teams at the events. It is lasercut out of a 6.5" x 5" piece of 1/8" thick MDF and requires only a rubber band to function. It also has 3 different pieces that will stop the arm at 15, 30, and 45-degrees away from vertical. The laser will leave partially cut tabs on the pieces so they won't fall out of the board without snapping them out manually so these make great handouts.

Printer:

Epilog Fusion Laser

Notes:

color FF0000 set to cut at 100% power and 8% speed

color 00FF00 set to engrave 75% power and 50% speed


Adjust the settings to fit whatever system you're using.

Assembly

Refer to labeled photo for part names.


Place tabs on side of arm into the round holes on the right and left sides. Be sure to keep the smooth side of the MDF towards the inside to reduce friction when the arm moves.
The mid and back crossbeams go on either side of where the arm is.
The top cross beam should be added next. It has the vertical slot to accommodate the angle stops.

Loop the rubber band twice around the center notched area of the arm so that it won't slide down and stretch towards the front. It should loop easily on the front crossbeam that is the last to be inserted


The angle stops should fit into the top crossbeam. A pin may be used to shim them into place or spread the fibers of the MDF so that they don't fall out.

The attached PDF is a Common Core standards-aligned lesson plan that will allow math teachers to use this catapult to include engineering concepts while still meeting the required standards.  I've taught this lesson in a 5th grade classroom in an urban public school and student engagement is high.

I designed this using Autodesk 123D Design. Here are the steps I took:

  1. Sketch the stand's side profile with a polyline, offset the line to the thickness I wanted the stand to be
  2. Extruded that to the width of the stand
  3. Carved out areas to make device home buttons easier to access
  4. For the cutouts on the stand faces, I sketched a rectangle on each face and cloned it.
  5. For the "strengthening ribs", I offset the edges of one side, trimmed all but the portions I needed for the two ribs on one side, further offset those portions (to create a "curved box"), extruded each box, chamfered the top edges of each box to end up with a "triangle" rib, copied the two ribs from one side to the other.
  6. Applied a small fillet to most of the edges
Inside each curve of the stand are "strengthening ribs" that greatly reduce the stand's flexion; I have put 10 pounds of pressure on the top of the stand and it doesn't flex more than an inch!

title: Wall Generator for table top games

description.text: So, I'm an avid DND player and DM, I always liked having small 3d printed bits on the table to help give it a bit more of a real feeling. Lately I wanted a skinnier (and quicker to make) version of the wall I had created a while back. So I tried to make this. You just put in the points you want the wall to go through, and it will make it. Sorry that the vector thing may be a bit complex, it didn't seem that hard when I was making it at first.

Notes:

A lot changes on how you make the wall, but I advise keeping the bottom the bottom.

Code explaination

So I'm still trying to find the best way to do this, (my github will probably do it better once I set that up right) but here goes nothing:

I'm using a recursive module that is basically an elaborate for loop. The extent of my error handling is if it is not a valid vector point don't make that segment. It draws a parallelogram (still working on making it sharper edges) then extrudes it wall height. Then checks to see if there are more points to be drawn and repeats.

//CUSTOMIZER VARIABLES

// This should be a small number relative to your height of wall
width_Of_wall = .05;

//How tall do you want this
height_Of_wall = 1;

// Vector path of wall, (wall thickness is only right angles for now), to generate a seperate path make a null/blank entry in your vector of order pairs, please note these are in whatever unit you selected earlier.
cords_Of_wall = [[1,0],[0,0],[0,1],[-1,1],[-1,3],[0,3],[0,4],[3,4],[4,3],[4,1],[3,1],[3,0],[2,0],[,],[1,1],[1,2],[2,2],[2,1],[1,1]];

//Basically are you using american units or real units
units_entered = 25.4;//[1:mm, 10:cm, 1000:meter, 25.4:inch, 304.8:foot]

//default is mm for most printers
desired_units_for_output = 1;//[1:mm, .1:cm, 0.001:meter, 0.0393701:inch, 0.00328084:foot]

// This option will not appear because of the *1
//CUSTOMIZER VARIABLES END

width_of_wall = width_Of_wall;
unit_conversion_factor = units_entereddesired_units_for_output;
height_of_wall = height_Of_wallunit_conversion_factor;

module make_wall_segments(cords = cords_Of_wall, number_your_on,units = 25.4) {
/number_your_on works such that when it equals 1, that is the begining.
(yes I am one of those people who belives arrays
should have started with 1 instead of 0)
/
point1 = cords[number_your_on-1]unit_conversion_factor;
point2 = cords[number_your_on]unit_conversion_factor;
point3 = [point2[0]+width_Of_wallunit_conversion_factor,point2[1]+width_Of_wallunit_conversion_factor];
point4 = [point1[0]+width_Of_wallunit_conversion_factor,point1[1]+width_Of_wallunit_conversion_factor];

linear_extrude(height = height_of_wall){
        polygon([point1,point2,point3,point4]);
    }
    if(number_your_on < len(cords)){
        make_wall_segments(cords = cords_Of_wall,number_your_on = number_your_on+1, units = unit_conversion_factor);
    }

}

make_wall_segments(cords = cords_Of_wall,number_your_on = 1, units = unit_conversion_factor);

description.text:
These are wider face plates for the Quanum V2 Goggles.

I tried gluing the weird rubber pads that come with the goggles onto the goggles when I got them, I ended up having to double them up to make them comfortable and they fell off after a day or two. Also, they were so narrow that they would push on parts of my face and really hurt.

The idea of these models is that they fit onto the Quanum V2 goggles (without needing glue) and create wider platforms to mount sponge pads on, to distribute the pressure on the wearers face.

I haven't got the right foam at the time of printing, but when I do, I will take pictures of that and update the models.

If you print the models on their side, they seem to print fairly well. I had some ripples with the printer I was using, but I don't think it is an inherent problem with the design its self.

I designed the top face plate from scratch to fit the goggles. The cheek plates were adapted from the "Face Contact Add-On for Quanum DIY V2 Goggles" models from ptuxbury.

If you have any comments or suggestions on how to improve the design let me know, or feel free to take it and adapt it as your own.

I needed to mount my older SIIG 10 outlet USB hub. It's in the 2 inch by 2 inch square tube form factor. I see the newer SIIG models look more like 2x1, so this won't work for those. I had the port mounted to my workstation stem with double-sided foam tape, but after a year of heavy hanging cords the tape finally gave out. Perfect application for something 3d printed!

This is a RepRap part for the Darwin design that I couldn't find, so I designed one. It will allow you to use common 608 skate bearings. This obsoletes the Z-Studding tie bracket, which require more material than this object, but needs no bearing (does need an M5 bolt and two nuts).
For other bearings, simply adjust "bearing_OD" and export the model with OpenSCAD.
The parametric model also includes a corner bracket based on accurate measurements of the STL file. This might be useful to someone! You can see it when you uncomment the following line:
//translate([-8.8,-8.8,-32-3]) corner_bracket();
If your Z-platform is not completely accurate, the slotted holes allow you to adjust the precise location of the bearings so that the platform exerts no force perpendicular to the threaded rod, just that it puts a static force on it because of its weight. This is very important to prevent a wobble which you could see across the vertical surfaces of all your prints.
Because you need 7 of these, or at least 3 of these at the bottom, I tried to minimize the material needed. Of course it can be further reduced, but I didn't want to push it before trying it first.
At 0.2 fill, the volume extruded is 4.8 cc and takes 25 minutes. At 0.45 fill (more than needed) it's 5.2 cc.
The bearing should press-fit into the part. If not, change the value of bearing_OD slightly. The hole is tapered, it\'s 0.1 mm wider at the top.

description.text:
'Platez' are fun, decorative and informative small car licence plate style signs. Use them around your home, office, in the garage or even attach them to your bike or 3D printer. Great for small display signs or as gifts. There are well over 150 'Platez' files so scroll through the files provided and choose your favourites to print.

Please post pictures of your 'Platez' in use!

In addition to the 'Platez' there are two additional .stl files. They are for a display stand and the other a hanger bracket so you can hang your Platez on door handles etc. (Refer to the images).

They are relatively quick and very easy to print. Just pause your machine at around 85% print progress and change the filament to a second colour. At standard scale they measure 95mm x 47.5mm (2:1 scale like most US car license plates). This makes them able to be printed on almost any 3D printer even if it only has a small build volume.... and they are only 3mm in depth so don't consume much filament.

'Platez' and the stand / hanger bracket are quick and easy prints but please refer to the print settings and images for additional information.... then have fun with them!

Note: If you like these check out the rest of my fun and practical designs.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator (5th Generation)

Resolution:

Standard / 0.20mm in PLA

Infill:

'Platez' - 2 shells / 15% infill recommended

Notes:

Recommend printing with a Raft for ease of removal from the build plate. No supports required for the Platez, the stand or the hanger bracket.

Print the stands and hanger brackets with 2 shells and 35% infill to make sure they are strong.

Change filament colours at approx. 85% print progress by pausing your machine. The text forming should be visible at that level.

Assemble with the Stand and Hanger Brakets

Once you've removed the Raft it's just a matter of mounting your 'Platez' onto the small pins in the Stand or inserting the Hanger Bracket into the back of your Platez.

Please note that the clearances used for the Stand pins and Hanger Bracket lugs should make them a firm to tight fit. This ensures they stay secure (particularly with the Hangar Bracket). With an accurate print they should work well straight away but will need a degree of pressure to secure them in place.

These have been tried and tested on MakerBot Replicator 2's and 5th Generation Replicators with great results!

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Oculus Rift DK1 includes 3 sets of lenses: A, B and C.

With this lens chooser you can test the lenses that best fit to you or others, without the need to test them with the Oculus Rift itself. Why? If you are showing the Rift to several friends, someone can be using the Rift while others are testing the other sets of lenses. Specially useful for people with glasses.

The lens chooser works only for one eye, but you may want to print two lens choosers to see the 3D effect with both eyes. Having separated devices for each eye enables you to have two people testing the lenses at the same time or to have one person enjoying the 3D effect.

description.text:
Fixed the lift screw, the original turns in the wrong direction which does not permit the marbles to climb the lift. I used 3/8" chrome Steel balls. Can be found cheap on ebay.

Lessons Learned:

  1. Use a floor fan to provide extra cooling for the lift screw, the edges can warp up if there is not enough cooling. The better it is cooled the smoother the lift operation.

  2. Add a small strip of plastic at the top of lift (see photos) that provides a lip for the marbles to flip over. This prevents the marbles from getting stuck at the top. Without it you would need to wait for another marble to come up and push the first one over.

  3. Add a small strip of plastic at the bottom of the lift (see photo) cover the rough surface of the PLA and help the marbles to slide right into the lift. Without it you would need to wait for a marble to hit the first one for it to enter the lift.

  4. The small cylinder of the bottom of the lift IS NECESSARY! If it breaks off just reprint it and use superglue to stick it back in place.

  5. I used superglue on the gear where it attaches to the motor (no patience for installing a set screw).

Ciao, ho creato questo porta olio e aceto con l'idea di riciclare le bottigliette di vetro (es. succhi di frutta, Crodino, Campari, Cinzano ecc) con diametro MAX di 46mm (altrimenti dovrete modificarlo).

A lavoro finito ho poi pensato di aggiungere anche una sezione per il sale e per il pepe.
Questa sezione non è stata incollata, ma va semplicemente ad incastro.
Anche qui ho aggiunto i bordi di altro colore.
Nel caso dei contenitori per il sale e il pepe, devono avere un diametro MAX di 40mm (altrimenti dovrete modificarlo).
Ho dovuto acquistare i contenitori del sale e del pepe, trovati a 1 euro ciascuno.
I tappi delle bottigliette dell'olio e dell'aceto si trovano facilmente e costano meno di 1 euro la confezione.

INGLESE
Hi, I created this item to recycle the little glass bottles (i.e. fruit juice, Crodino, Campari, Cinzano ecc) with MAX diameter of 46mm (otherwise you have to modify it).
I thought to add some detail and gluing them with super glue.
When completed, I then thought to also add a section to the salt and pepper.
This section has not been pasted, but simply goes interlocking.
I added other color edges.
The salt and pepper shakers must have a diameter of 40mm MAX (otherwise you have to modify it).
I had to buy salt and pepper shakers, found at 1 euro each.
The caps of the oil and vinegar bottles are easy to find and cost less than 1 euro a pack.
